Step Six: Build a Content Strategy That Supports the Entire Buyer Journey
Content is the fuel that powers your entire GTM engine. Without it, your demand generation programs have nothing to offer, your email sequences have nothing to say, and your sales team has nothing to share with prospects.

In 2026, the content challenge is not about volume. It is about building content that earns credibility, answers real buyer questions, and shows up in the places buyers are looking, including AI-generated search results.

B2B buyers are becoming increasingly likely to inform their purchase decisions with assistance from large language models like ChatGPT and Google Gemini. The age of AI discoverability will democratize B2B marketing and shift the strategy from building awareness through budget and keywords to building a credibility-driven reputation across the public internet.

This means your content strategy needs to prioritize depth, accuracy, and original perspective over keyword stuffing and generic thought leadership. It means answering the specific questions your buyers are actually asking, not just the questions your marketing team thinks they are asking.

A GTM-aligned content strategy maps content to each stage of the buyer journey:

Awareness Stage: Educational content that helps buyers understand the problem they are facing. This includes blog posts, research reports, industry guides, and webinars that establish your brand as a credible voice in the space.

Consideration Stage: Content that helps buyers evaluate their options and understand the criteria for making a good decision. This includes comparison guides, case studies, ROI calculators, and product explainer videos.

Decision Stage: Content that gives buyers the confidence to choose you. This includes customer success stories, reference calls, implementation guides, and risk mitigation resources that address the final objections standing between a prospect and a signed contract.

The focus has shifted from content generation to discovery optimization and data-driven targeting, including Answer Engine Optimization (AEO), where marketers are restructuring content to appear in AI-generated search results and recommendation engines.

Step Seven: Measure What Matters and Optimize Continuously
A GTM strategy is not a one-time document. It is a living system that needs to be monitored, measured, and refined based on what the data tells you.

The challenge for many B2B marketing teams in 2026 is that they are measuring the wrong things. Vanity metrics like website traffic, email open rates, and social media impressions look good in reports but tell you very little about whether your GTM strategy is actually driving revenue.

The metrics that matter for GTM success in 2026:

Pipeline contribution by channel and campaign
MQL-to-SQL conversion rate, with anything below 10% signaling an ICP or qualification problem
Sales cycle length by lead source and persona
Customer acquisition cost (CAC) by channel
Average contract value and revenue per account
Win rate on marketing-sourced deals
Time to first meeting from initial outreach
B2B leaders focused on buyer experience close deals 31% faster. High digital maturity suppliers reported 6.1% average revenue growth versus 2.9% for low-maturity competitors. The data is clear: companies that invest in measuring and optimizing the buyer experience outgrow their peers by a significant margin.

Building a cadence of regular GTM reviews, monthly at minimum, ensures that your strategy stays responsive to market changes, competitive moves, and shifting buyer behavior. When a channel underperforms, you adjust. When a campaign overperforms, you double down.

