Common GTM Mistakes B2B Companies Must Avoid in 2026
Even well-resourced companies make avoidable mistakes in their GTM execution. Understanding where strategies typically break down can save you months of wasted time and budget.

Skipping ICP validation: Many companies build their GTM strategy around assumptions about who their ideal customer is rather than validated data. The result is a misaligned campaign strategy that generates plenty of activity but very little revenue.

Treating all channels equally: Not every channel delivers equal returns for every business. Your GTM strategy should be based on where your specific buyers actually spend their time and what types of content they consume, not what worked for a competitor in a different vertical.

Neglecting the mid and bottom funnel: Many B2B marketing programs invest heavily in awareness and lead generation but leave prospects to fend for themselves once they enter the funnel. Mid-funnel nurture programs, personalized follow-up sequences, and sales enablement content are just as critical to GTM success as top-of-funnel demand generation.

Over-automating without personalizing: Automation at scale without signal-based personalization increases unsubscribes and kills reply rates. More volume with bad targeting is just faster failure.

Ignoring customer success as a GTM lever: Your existing customers are your most powerful GTM asset. Case studies, referrals, and expansion revenue from happy customers cost a fraction of what it takes to acquire new ones. Make customer success a core part of your GTM motion, not an afterthought.

